2591198	when a military parent be deploy to a combat zone , the child leave behind might be plague by more than frightening dream and ache heart .
2591199	a new study fund by the U.S. Army find that child abuse and neglect be about 40 percent higher in Army household during combat-related deployment than during non-deployment -- and that civilian mother be significantly more likely to mistreat they child than civilian father .
2591200	researcher in North Carolina track nearly 1,800 Army family with at least one substantiate incident of `` child maltreatment '' through period of deployment and non-deployment from 2001 to 2004 .
2591201	the study , one of the first to examine child mistreatment in military family during deployment , find that the rate of physical abuse by female civilian parent be nearly twice as great during time of deployment .
2591202	the rate of child neglect by civilian mother be nearly four time higher during deployment .
2591203	however , the rate of child mistreatment be not significantly elevated for male civilian parent during deployment .
2591204	Deborah A. Gibbs , lead author of the study and a senior analyst with RTI International , a independent , nonprofit research institute in North Carolina , say the report be part of a larger study of family violence in the military .
2591205	the child mistreatment portion of the study emerge when many soldier be be deploy to war in Iraq and Afghanistan , Gibbs say .
2591206	`` it be easy to imagine that deployment would increase stress on the parent who be leave behind , '' she say .
2591207	Gibbs say moderate to severe mistreatment of child be about 60 percent higher during deployment .
2591208	she say the rating of moderate and severe mistreatment depend both on the risk of harm to the child and the actual harm .
2591209	for example , mild abuse could be inappropriate discipline ; severe abuse could be a action that result in significant injury .
2591210	Gibbs say the finding be generally consistent across age , rank and ethnic group .
2591211	James E. McCarroll , director of the Family Violence Research Project in the Center for the study of traumatic stress at Uniform Services University of the Health Sciences in Maryland , say the study confirm other research , include he own .
2591212	the study 's result do not surprise Michelle Joyner , director of communication for the virginia-based National Military Family Association , a nonprofit advocacy group that focus on quality of life issue for military family .
2591213	`` we know in we dealings with military family that family be tire , '' she say .
2591214	Gibbs say recent research suggest the rate of child abuse and neglect in military family be lower than in the general population prior to large-scale deployment .
2591215	but when deployment increase , the rate of mistreatment in the military population rise sharply and eventually become higher than in the civilian population .
2591216	while most military family do a `` tremendous job '' of handle the stress of deployment , she say many still need access to additional service , like child care and support group .
