3795686	FORT MCMURRAY , Alberta
3795687	the Aurora Mine exude the odor of petroleum and the look of untapped riches .
3795688	the open pit mine plunge 250 foot deep and range over a couple of square mile , carve out of pine and spruce forest by gigantic machine that operate 24\/7 , even in the dark of winter at 40 degree below zero .
3795689	this be the heart of Alberta 's oil sand , a remote florida-sized region where moose , bear and beaver inhabit watery woodland atop the world 's largest proven petroleum reserve outside Saudi Arabia .
3795690	the unusual deposit -- where oil be lock in the tarry soil rather than pooled beneath the surface -- be yield a bonanza of investment dollar , government revenue and job .
3795691	almost half of Canada 's oil production come from the oil sand -- and the energy industry estimate that enough oil can be extract to fill the country 's need for three century .
3795692	the vast majority of canadian oil export go to the United States , and the Bush administration see the remain resource as America 's best hope for reduce dependence on Middle Eastern oil .
3795693	`` no single thing can do more to help we reach that goal than realize the potential of the oil sand , '' U.S. Energy Secretary Samuel Bodman say during a visit last July .
3795694	the benefit might be great , but the toll on other natural resource be also enormous .
3795695	separate petroleum from sand burn so much natural gas that the enterprise be become Canada 's largest source of greenhouse gas emission growth .
3795696	the oil sand lie within a major intact ecosystem , the boreal forest cover almost one-third of Canada 's land mass .
3795697	the forest be one of the world 's biggest freshwater storehouse and absorb a vast amount of carbon dioxide .
3795698	it also provide habitat for hundred of species of bird and be home to caribous , wolf and bear .
3795699	expansion of the oil sand operation could tear huge hole in a forest already rent by log , oil and gas exploration and other industry .
3795700	with development expect to triple , or even quintuple , in the next few decade , producer and government official puzzle over how to harness the oil sand ' potential with less cost to the climate , land , water and the well-being of native people who fear that cancer case in a downstream community might be a sign of lethal industrial pollution .
3795701	current lease for open-pit mining cover a area several time the size of New York City , accord to the Pembina Institute , a environmental research group in Alberta .
3795702	but more than 50,000 square mile be potentially available for various type of oil extraction , which have prompt environmentalist to call for stop development until ecological effect can be reduce .
3795703	`` the very nature of oil sand mean that develop they ... cause a incredible disruption to land and landscape over immense area , '' say a March report by the House of Commons natural resource committee .
3795704	although the U.S. be the primary market for the oil , pressure for development also come from chinese company that have be invest hundred of million of dollar in lease .
3795705	cavernous pit mine account for the bulk of the 1.2 million barrel of oil generate daily in a region with a estimate 174 billion barrel in reserve .
3795706	Syncrude Canada Ltd. , a joint venture that include Exxon Mobil Corp.-controlled Imperial Oil Resources , have 8,000 worker ; it spend $ 4.2 billion last year and have invest billion more in capital improvement .
3795707	`` it be not a business for the faint of heart , '' spokesman Alain Moore say .
3795708	at Syncrude 's Aurora Mine , dozen of electric shovel eat away at the tarry deposit .
3795709	with each scoop , the behemoth drop 100 ton of dirt into truck with bed as big as small house .
3795710	amid cloud of dust , the truck deliver they payload to machinery that crush and screen it before it be mix with hot water and pipe into a cone-shaped tank .
3795711	a form of petroleum call bitumen rise to the top , then be upgrade in a maze of smoke stack , pipe and steel structure as high as 23 story .
3795712	the leftovers be stockpile on the surround landscape .
3795713	huge yellow block of sulfur impurity be stack pyramid-fashion .
3795714	Dunes of sand expel from the plant sweep toward the horizon .
3795715	on lake-sized tailing pond , float scarecrow and fire from air cannon discourage bird from alight on the oily wastewater and die .
3795716	recover oil from sand require the use of natural gas to heat water , which produce greenhouse gas and other air pollutant .
3795717	the water itself be draw from the 765-mile-long Athabasca River , which flow from glacier in the canadian Rockies through numerous small community and sustain waterfowl , fish and other wildlife .
3795718	although improve technology and recycle have reduce the amount of water and energy need for each barrel of oil , Syncrude 's report show overall quantity grow along with oil production .
3795719	the oil sand operation account for 4 percent of Canada 's greenhouse gas emission in 2005 , and energy regulator say they have be increase .
3795720	University of Alberta ecologist David Schindler project that new development , couple with climate change , could cut the Athabasca River 's low winter flow in half or more by midcentury .
3795721	`` what they want to withdraw be a unsustainable amount , '' he say .
3795722	Alberta environmental official recently establish water-use rule to prevent biological damage to the river , and the provincial government have require a 12 percent reduction in greenhouse gas emission per barrel of oil .
3795723	but expert at the Pembina Institute maintain that those measure be inadequate .
3795724	the industry , which contribute billion of dollar in economic activity , royalty and tax each year , say it plan to minimize environmental effect through improve efficiency and through land restoration require by government lease .
3795725	Syncrude report that it have reclaim one-quarter of the land disturb by mining , although the government have not certify the land 's ability to sustain wildlife and plant .
3795726	Greg Stringham , vice president of the Canadian Association of Petroleum Producers , say oil-sand operator be look at alternative to natural gas for heating water , include start controlled fire underground or use nuclear power .
3795727	some company , he say , be look at way to sequester carbon dioxide underground .
3795728	`` the government do not want to shut down the development because it provide benefit -lrb- to the country -rrb- and revenue to they , '' Stringham say .
3795729	`` all anyone can hope for be the best available technology , not just stop produce oil . ''
3795730	even people who claim harm from the fallout say the oil boom have its advantage .
3795731	Ivy Simpson , who work at a all-terrain vehicle dealership , develop cervical cancer 10 year ago .
3795732	Simpson believe she be expose to pollution from oil development while live in the downstream hamlet of Fort Chipewyan .
3795733	but she later take a job at a mine for about $ 30 a hour -- enough to pay rent and buy a truck .
3795734	`` be a single mom and recently widow , I need the work , and I have to pay the bill , '' say Simpson , 28 .
3795735	`` it be expensive to live here . ''
3795736	Fort Chipewyan , the oldest settlement in Alberta , be a 50-minute flight and world away from Fort McMurray .
3795737	the town 's quiet street run between dense wood and the rocky shoreline of Lake Athabasca , which receive water from the Athabasca and other river .
3795738	`` to have a lake like this and not be able to drink from it be a real shame , '' say Ray Ladouceur , 65 , a commercial fisherman who have catch fish with humped back , cyst and other deformity .
3795739	`` I call this a red zone , a danger zone , to live in . ''
3795740	a industry-funded water-monitoring program that include government agency and environmental group have study fish in the river but not the lake .
